from langsmith import Client
from dotenv import load_dotenv

# Load environment variables from .env file
load_dotenv()

client = Client()
dataset_name = "Analogies"

inputs = [
    "Please explain Recursion.",
    "Please explain gravity.",
    "Integrals are hard, please help",
    "How do magnets work?",
    "How does electricity power devices?",
    "Does the internet work like power and water? Is it flowing through the wires?",
    "How come metal gets hot really fast?",
    "Man I just don't get Fourier transforms at all",
    "What can you tell me about the Krebs Cycle?",
    "What are ionic bonds? Can atoms use those to form molecules?"
]

outputs = [
    "Sure! Imagine you’re building a giant LEGO tower. To make it easier, you decide to use a special technique: you’ll build smaller LEGO towers first, and then stack them on top of each other to create the big one.\n\n    Here’s how it works:\n\n    Building the Small Towers: You start with the smallest part, say a 3-brick high tower. To build this small tower, you use the same method you’ll use for the big one: you take a few bricks, put them together, and repeat this until the tower is complete.\n\n    Stacking the Small Towers: Once you have enough of these small towers, you stack them on top of each other to form the big LEGO tower.\n\n    In this analogy:\n\n    Recursion is like the process of building the small towers. Each small tower is built using the same steps as the bigger one, just on a smaller scale.\n    The small towers are like the \"recursive steps,\" where the problem (building the tower) is solved in smaller, simpler parts.\n    Stacking the towers represents combining these smaller solutions to solve the bigger problem.\n    So, recursion is a method where a problem is solved by breaking it down into smaller, similar problems. Each small problem is solved in the same way as the larger one, just on a smaller scale. This process continues until you reach a simple enough problem that can be solved directly. Then you combine all these solutions to get the answer to the original, larger problem.",
    "Imagine you're at a park with a big trampoline. If you place a heavy ball, like a bowling ball, in the center of the trampoline, what happens? The trampoline sags or dips down around the ball. Now, if you take a smaller ball, like a tennis ball, and roll it near the heavy ball, you'll see that the tennis ball starts to roll towards the bowling ball.\r\n\r\nIn this analogy:\r\n\r\nThe trampoline represents space.\r\nThe heavy ball represents a planet, like Earth.\r\nThe small ball represents a smaller object, like a person or a satellite.\r\nThe way the trampoline sags around the heavy ball is similar to how gravity works. Gravity is the force that pulls objects towards one another. Just like the tennis ball rolls towards the heavy ball because of the dip in the trampoline, objects like us are pulled towards Earth because of the force of gravity.\r\n\r\nSo, gravity is like a trampoline that pulls everything towards the Earth, making sure things stay grounded and don\u2019t just float away.",
    "Here\u2019s a step-by-step way to understand integrals using a pizza analogy:\r\n\r\nBasic Concept - Slicing the Pizza: Think of a pizza with a really weird shape that you need to measure. To find out how much pizza you have, you can\u2019t just use the usual area formulas for simple shapes. Instead, imagine slicing the pizza into lots of very thin, skinny slices. Each slice is very narrow and can be approximated as a thin rectangle.\r\n\r\nCalculating Each Slice: For each of these thin slices, you can calculate the area of the slice. Even though each slice is very thin, it\u2019s easy to figure out the area of these narrow rectangles.\r\n\r\nAdding Up the Slices: To find the total area of the pizza, you add up the areas of all these tiny slices. Because there are so many slices, each with a very small area, the total is a good approximation of the pizza\u2019s area.\r\n\r\nMaking the Slices Thinner - Integral Concept: As you make the slices thinner and thinner, your approximation gets better and better. In calculus, the integral is like taking this idea to the limit. Instead of slicing into just a bunch of narrow rectangles, we imagine an infinite number of infinitely thin slices and add them all up. This process gives us the exact area under the curve.",
    "Imagine you have a toy that can only stick to some things, like metal objects, but not to anything else. Now, if you have two of these magic toys and try to push them together, they might either stick together or push away from each other.\r\n\r\nHere\u2019s how it works with magnets:\r\n\r\nMagnetic Power: Magnets have an invisible force around them, kind of like an invisible hug that they can give to some metal things. You can\u2019t see this force, but it\u2019s there, like the air we breathe.\r\n\r\nMagnet Ends: Magnets have two special ends. One end is called North, and the other end is South. If you bring the North end of one magnet close to the South end of another magnet, they will stick together, like how two different ends of a toy might snap together. But if you try to bring two North ends or two South ends together, they will push away from each other, like how two similar toy ends might repel.\r\n\r\nSpecial Metals: Only certain metals like iron can feel this invisible force from the magnet and stick to it. Other things don\u2019t respond to this force.\r\n\r\nSo, magnets are like magic toys that have an invisible force that can make some metals stick to them or push away, depending on how their ends line up.",
    "Imagine a water wheel at a river. When water flows over the wheel, it makes the wheel spin. Here\u2019s how this relates to electricity making devices work:\r\n\r\nElectric Flow as Water: Think of electricity like the flowing water that moves through pipes. In an electric circuit, this flow is made up of tiny particles called electrons, which move through wires just like water flows through a hose.\r\n\r\nDevices as Water Wheels: Now, imagine that your light bulb, TV, or toy is like a water wheel. Just as the water wheel spins when water flows over it, these devices \u201Cwork\u201D when electricity flows through them. The electricity provides the energy needed for them to do their job.\r\n\r\nInside the Device: Inside your light bulb, for example, there\u2019s a thin wire called a filament. When electricity flows through this filament, it gets very hot and starts to glow, which is what makes the light. It\u2019s similar to how the water wheel spins when the water flows over it.\r\n\r\nSwitches and Controls: When you turn on a switch, it\u2019s like opening a valve to let water flow. When the switch is on, electricity can flow through the device, making it work. When the switch is off, it\u2019s like closing the valve; the flow stops, and the device stops working.\r\n\r\nSo, in summary: Electricity flows through wires to reach a device, and this flow is like water moving over a wheel. Inside the device, the electricity does its job, making things happen\u2014like lighting up a bulb or powering a toy.",
    "Great question! The internet is a bit like a super high-speed delivery system, and while it doesn't work exactly like water or electricity, we can use a similar analogy to make it easier to understand.\r\n\r\n1. **The Internet as a Mail Delivery System**: Imagine the internet is like a giant, super-fast mail delivery service. Instead of delivering letters and packages, it delivers information. The \u201Cmail\u201D here could be anything from a picture of a cat to a video game you\u2019re playing online.\r\n\r\n2. **Data as Packages**: The information you send or receive over the internet is like little packages. Each package contains a piece of the whole picture or message you want to send or get. These packages are called \u201Cdata.\u201D\r\n\r\n3. **Wires and Cables as Roads**: The wires and cables that carry the internet are like roads and highways. Just like cars travel on roads to deliver packages, data travels through these wires to get from one place to another.\r\n\r\n4. **Routers as Post Offices**: Routers and other network devices are like post offices or sorting centers. They help direct the data (the packages) to the right place. If you want to send a package to a friend, the post office figures out the best route. Similarly, routers figure out the best path for your data to reach the right computer or phone.\r\n\r\n5. **Speed and Efficiency**: Just like some roads are faster and better maintained than others, some internet connections are faster and more efficient than others. This is why sometimes websites load quickly, and other times they might be slow\u2014it's like having a smooth highway versus a bumpy road.\r\n\r\nSo, while the internet doesn't flow like water or electricity, it uses wires (like roads) to carry information (like packages) to different places, with routers acting like post offices that help direct the data where it needs to go.",
    "Let's imagine you're playing with different kinds of materials, like metal, plastic, and wood. You want to know why metal gets hot faster than the others.\r\n\r\nThink of heat like a bunch of tiny, invisible marbles bouncing around. When you heat something up, you're actually giving those marbles a lot of energy, so they move around really quickly.\r\n\r\nNow, imagine different materials as different types of playground equipment. Metal is like a very smooth, fast slide. When you give the marbles energy, they zip around quickly because the slide is smooth and allows them to move easily.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, plastic and wood are like bumpy slides. The marbles don't move as fast because the bumps and roughness slow them down.\r\n\r\nIn scientific terms, metals have particles (like atoms) that are very close together and can pass energy quickly from one to the next. This is why metal heats up fast. In materials like plastic or wood, the particles are further apart and not as good at passing energy around, so they heat up more slowly.\r\n\r\nSo, metals get hot quickly because their particles are like a super smooth slide for the marbles of heat energy!",
    "Imagine you have a big, delicious cake in front of you, and it\u2019s decorated with different flavors. You know that the cake is made up of layers of chocolate, vanilla, and maybe a few other flavors. But right now, you can only taste the whole cake, not the individual flavors.\r\n\r\nA Fourier transform is like a magical tool that lets you figure out what flavors are in the cake and how much of each flavor there is, even though you can only taste the whole thing at once.\r\n\r\nHere's a step-by-step analogy:\r\n\r\nThe Cake (Signal): Think of the whole cake as a signal, which could be anything from a sound wave to a light signal. It\u2019s a mix of different components, just like the cake is a mix of different flavors.\r\n\r\nIndividual Flavors (Frequency Components): Each layer of flavor in the cake represents a different frequency in our signal. For example, the chocolate flavor could represent low frequencies, while the vanilla might represent higher frequencies.\r\n\r\nTasting Each Flavor (Fourier Transform): When you use a Fourier transform, it\u2019s like being able to taste each flavor separately even though they\u2019re mixed in the cake. The Fourier transform helps you see how much of each frequency is present in your signal.\r\n\r\nThe Recipe (Frequency Spectrum): Once you\u2019ve figured out the flavors, you can write down the recipe. This recipe is like the frequency spectrum, which tells you exactly what frequencies (flavors) are in the signal and in what amounts.\r\n\r\nSo, in summary, a Fourier transform takes a complex signal (the cake) and breaks it down into simpler parts (the individual flavors) so you can understand what\u2019s inside it.",
    "Let's imagine the Krebs Cycle as a busy kitchen where a chef (the cell) is preparing a delicious meal (energy) from various ingredients (nutrients).\r\n\r\nStarting Ingredients: Think of the Krebs Cycle as a recipe that begins with a special ingredient called acetyl-CoA, which is like a starter kit in our kitchen. This ingredient comes from the breakdown of carbohydrates, fats, and proteins from the food we eat.\r\n\r\nThe Recipe: In our kitchen, the chef has a set of steps to follow. These steps involve mixing acetyl-CoA with another ingredient called oxaloacetate to make a new dish called citrate. This is like combining flour and sugar to make a dough.\r\n\r\nCooking Process: The chef then cooks this mixture through a series of steps. Each step involves adding or removing ingredients (like spices and flavors) to transform the mixture. During this process, several changes happen, and different molecules are produced, including something called NADH and FADH2. These are like the different cooking tools and flavors that help make our dish perfect.\r\n\r\nEnergy Production: At the end of the cooking process, the chef gets a final product that\u2019s full of energy, which can be used by the cell to do work, like powering muscles or keeping everything functioning properly. This final product is ready to be used or stored for later.\r\n\r\nRecycling: After cooking, some ingredients from the final dish are recycled back into the beginning of the recipe. This is like cleaning up your kitchen and getting everything ready for the next meal.\r\n\r\nIn simple terms, the Krebs Cycle is like a kitchen recipe where the cell breaks down nutrients into useful energy, with a bit of recycling to keep the process going smoothly.",
    "Imagine you have two kids, Alice and Bob, each with a handful of marbles. Alice has a lot of marbles, and Bob has only a few. Now, Alice and Bob decide to trade marbles. Alice, who has extra marbles, gives some to Bob, who needs more. After the trade, they are both happy because Alice still has plenty of marbles, and Bob now has more.\r\n\r\nIn this analogy:\r\n\r\nThe marbles represent electrons, which are tiny particles that orbit around the center of an atom.\r\nAlice represents an atom that has extra electrons.\r\nBob represents an atom that needs more electrons.\r\nIn the world of atoms, some atoms have extra electrons they don\u2019t need, while others are missing electrons they really want. When these atoms come close together, the one with extra electrons will give some away to the one that needs them. This exchange creates a strong attraction between the two atoms. This attraction is called an ionic bond.\r\n\r\nSo, an ionic bond is like a special kind of friendship between two atoms. One atom gives away electrons, and the other atom receives them. Because of this exchange, the atoms become attracted to each other and stick together very tightly.\r\n\r\nYes, atoms can use ionic bonds to form molecules! When atoms bond this way, they form compounds. For example, when sodium (which has extra electrons) and chlorine (which needs more electrons) come together, they form salt (sodium chloride). The sodium gives an electron to chlorine, and they stick together with their new \"electronic friendship.\""
]

# Store
dataset = client.create_dataset(
    dataset_name=dataset_name,
    description="QA pairs for STEM Analogies",
)
client.create_examples(
    inputs=[{"question": q} for q in inputs],
    outputs=[{"answer": a} for a in outputs],
    dataset_id=dataset.id,
)